<h2>The Rise of Agentic Commerce</h2>
<p>Agentic AI is not just changing how marketers work. It is changing how customers buy. This shift has major implications for every <a href="/blog/content-marketing-strategy/">content marketing strategy</a>.</p>
<h3>How Agent-to-Agent Commerce Works</h3>
<p>When a consumer asks their AI assistant "Find me the best running shoes under $150 with good arch support," the consumer's agent queries brand agents, compares options, and presents a shortlist. No Google search. No browsing 12 websites. No reading reviews.</p>
<p><a href="https://hbr.org/2026/03/preparing-your-brand-for-agentic-ai">Harvard Business Review</a> identifies three interaction types:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Brand agents.</strong> Company-controlled AI that represents the brand (like Instacart's ChatGPT plugin).</li>
<li><strong>Consumer agents.</strong> Independent AI assistants that shop on behalf of the customer (like ChatGPT, Perplexity, or Google Gemini).</li>
<li><strong>Full AI intermediation.</strong> Agent-to-agent transactions where no human is involved in the purchase decision.</li>
</ol>
<p>Gartner projects that 90% of B2B buying will be AI-agent intermediated by 2028, pushing $15 trillion through agent exchanges.</p>
<h3>What This Means for Marketers</h3>
